      <hedline>
        <hl1>Global Warming</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Paul Feiner letter on September 1 article on impact of global warming on national parks recalls recent tour of Alaskan glaciers and expresses hope they will still be there for his great-great-grandchildren</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: I read ''Global Warming an Issue for National Parks'' (Sept. 1) on the plane coming home from a tour of the Alaskan glaciers. The highlight of my vacation was a helicopter ride to the spectacular Juneau icefield glaciers. Landing and walking on the glacier and viewing the spectacular scenery was awesome. It was sad to hear the stories of how glaciers in the low elevations have been thinning by several hundred feet in the last 40 years, and of how glaciers have retreated so substantially in just the last 10 years.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: I read ''Global Warming an Issue for National Parks'' (Sept. 1) on the plane coming home from a tour of the Alaskan glaciers. The highlight of my vacation was a helicopter ride to the spectacular Juneau icefield glaciers. Landing and walking on the glacier and viewing the spectacular scenery was awesome. It was sad to hear the stories of how glaciers in the low elevations have been thinning by several hundred feet in the last 40 years, and of how glaciers have retreated so substantially in just the last 10 years.</p>
        <p>I hope my great-great-grandchildren will be able to enjoy stepping and walking on an Alaskan glacier -- just as I did. Glaciers must not be allowed to become an endangered species.</p>
        <p>PAUL FEINER  Greenburgh, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
